canonical:
  title: 謝表
  author: 李齊賢
  language: lzh
  text: 乾坤邈矣敢期呼籲之聞草木微哉忽致恩榮之沐感驚交至蹈舞不知云云體禹儉勤躋湯聖敬遵祖宗之興禮雖舊惟新擁廟社之休祥於斯爲盛兼屈聽卑之鑑克敦字小之仁眷言出日之邦生我俔天之妹美鍾坤順遵母儀於六宮慶毓离明固邦本於萬世於是降璿源之貴戚馳玉節之重臣陳飮食以賜歡賁金繒而將意旣醉以德爲永好於舅甥不顯其光想歆觀於夷夏臣敢不念其卵翼報以粉糜專述職於箕封每輸誠於華祝
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝表
  author: 李齊賢
  language: lzh
  text: 乾坤邈矣。敢期呼籲之聞。草木微哉。忽致恩榮之沐。感驚交至。蹈舞不知。云云。體禹儉勤。躋湯聖敬。遵祖宗之興禮。雖舊惟新。擁廟社之休祥。於斯爲盛。兼屈聽卑之鑑。克敦字小之仁。眷言出日之邦。生我俔天之妹。美鍾坤順。遵母儀於六宮。慶毓离明。固邦本於萬世。於是降璿源之貴戚。馳玉節之重臣。陳飮食以賜歡。賁金繒而將意。旣醉以德。爲永好於舅甥。不顯其光。想歆觀於夷夏。臣敢不念其卵翼。報以粉糜。專述職於箕封。每輸誠於華祝。
korean:
  title: 사표
  author: 이제현
  language: kor
  text: 하늘이 머온지라 감히 부르짖음이 들리기를 기억하였사오리까마는, 초목이 미세하여도 문득 은혜와 영광에 목욕함을 받았나이다. 느껍고 놀라움에 겹쳐 이르매 저도 모르게 뛰고 춤추어지나이다. 운운. 우(禹)의 검소함과 부지런함을 본받으며, 탕(湯)의 성경(聖敬)에 나아가서조종(祖宗)이 예(禮)를 일으킨 것을 따르니 비록 옛나라이나 국운(國運)이 새로우며, 종묘 사직의 아름다운 성서를 차지한 것이 오늘에 융성하나이다. 겸하여 낮은 것을 구부리고 듣는 밝음을 베푸시어 능히 소국 사랑하는 인(仁)을 도탑게 하시나이다. 해 뜨는 나라를 돌보시어 우리 천녀(天女)를 낳으셨으니, 덕은 곤순(坤順)을 타고 났음에 육궁(六宮)에 모도(母道)를 따랐고, 세자(世子)를 낳는 경사 있음에 나라 근본을 만세(萬世)에 굳게 하셨나이다. 이에 선원(璿源)의 귀척(貴戚)을 내려 보내어 옥절(玉節)의 중신(重臣)으로 달려오게 하셨나이다. 이미 덕으로써 취하게 하심에 구생(舅甥)간에 영원한 정을 맺으시니 그 빛이 나타나지 않으오리까. 아마도 이(夷)와 중화(中華)에서 흠선하게 보리이다. 신은 감히 날개로 알을 덮어 주듯 한 그 은혜를 생각하여 분골쇄신(粉骨碎身)으로 보답하여, 오로지 기자(箕子)의 봉토(封土)에 속국의 직분을 다하고, 매양 화봉인(華封人)의 축수에 정성을 바치지 아니하오리까.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0400_010_0450&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 탕(湯)의 …… 나아가서 : '
    value: 《서경》에 “탕(湯)의 성스러움과 공경함이 날로 오른다[聖敬日躋].”라는 말이 있다.
english:
  title: Memorial of Gratitude
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven lies distant—how could I dare hope my voice would ever be heard? Yet I am but a blade of grass, and lo, I have been blessed with favor and honor beyond measure. Gratitude and amazement flood through me; I find myself dancing without knowing it. And so...

    I have endeavored to emulate the frugality and diligence of Yu the Great, to ascend toward the sacred reverence of Tang the Sage. Following in the footsteps of my ancestors who established the way of ritual, though their age is past, their spirit remains ever new. Holding fast to the auspicious blessings of temple and altar, our prosperity reaches its zenith in this very day. Moreover, through your gracious humility and benevolent listening, you have perfected the compassion befitting a great nation. You have watched over the lands where the sun rises and brought forth the Celestial Daughter to our people. Her virtue flows from the perfect compliance of earth itself; she embodies the mother's way throughout the six palaces, and through the blessing of an heir, she has secured the nation's foundation for ten thousand generations.

    Thus you have dispatched from the imperial house a noble kinsman bearing the jade tablet of high office, bearing gifts of food and wine to honor our union. Through your generosity, uncle and nephew are bound in eternal affection. Should not this light shine forth for all the world to see—in distant lands and the civilized realm alike? How could your humble servant forget such care, as precious as wings sheltering an egg? With every fiber of my being I shall repay this grace, dedicating myself to fulfill my duties as a tributary state within the domain of Ki-ja, and offering my steadfast devotion to the blessings pronounced by the ancients.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yu the Great and Tang the Sage are celebrated exemplars of ancient Chinese virtue and governance, representing humility and reverence respectively.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'six palaces' refer to the imperial harem; 'mother's way' refers to the proper conduct expected of an empress.
  - key: ''
    value: Ki-ja was a legendary sage who is said to have founded a kingdom in ancient Korea, making the reference both historically and culturally significant to a Korean audience.
  - key: ''
    value: '''The lands where the sun rises'' poetically refers to Korea''s eastern location.'
